A '''coin of account''' is a unit of [[money]] that does not exist as an actual [[coin]] (that is, a metal disk) but is used in figuring prices or other amounts of money.

==Examples==
===Mill===
The ''[[mill (currency)|mill]]'' (or sometimes, ''mil'') is a coin of account in the United States.  It is equal to one-tenth of a [[penny]], and so to one-thousandth of a dollar (= $0.001), whence the name, which means "thousandth." There was never such a coin [[mint (coin)|mint]]ed by the U.S. Federal government, though some states minted these coins well into the mid-1900s. Coins of account are used in accounting and for figuring [[tax]]es, usually either [[property tax]]es or [[sales tax]]es.

===Guinea===
From 1816 to the 1980s the [[Guinea_(British_coin)#Replacement_by_the_pound|British Guinea]] was no longer used a coin but prices for luxury items and professional services were often quoted in guineas, on the understanding that a guinea was equal to 21 shillings.

