{{Use Indian English|date=May 2016}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}} {{infobox caste | caste_name =Kongu Vellalar | image = | caption = | varna = | classification = [[Backward Class]] | gotra = | religions = [[Hinduism]] | country = [[India]] | state = [[Tamil Nadu]] | populated_states = Major Population in [[Tamil Nadu]], Minor Populations in [[Karnataka]], [[Kerala]], United Kingdom and the United States<ref>{{cite news | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Gounder-consolidation-could-pose-headache-to-major-parties/articleshow/4557663.cms?referral=PM | title=Gounder consolidation could pose headache to major parties | first=Jayaraj | last=Sivan | newspaper=The Times of India | date=21 May 2009 | accessdate=22 May 2016 }}</ref> | languages = [[Tamil language|Tamil]] ([[Kongu Tamil]]) | region = [[Kongu Nadu]] | related = [[Thuluva Vellalar]] }}
'''Kongu Vellalars''', sometimes referred to simply as [[Gounder (title)|Gounder]], are a community from the western region of [[Tamil Nadu]], which is known as [[Kongu Nadu]]. It also refers to the title or surname used by the [[Vellalar]] community from the region. Kongu Vellala Gounders were classified as a [[Forward Caste]] at the time of [[Partition of India|Indian independence]] but they successfully requested to be reclassified as a [[Backward Class]] in 1975.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/article277921.ece | newspaper=The Hindu | title=Looking to create a Kongu stronghold | date=8 May 2009 | first=K.V. | last=Prasad | accessdate=22 May 2016}}</ref> The Vellalars of Kongu region came to be known as Kongu Vellalar or Gounder, though both the names have also been treated separately in some regions.<ref>{{cite book |title=Historical Dictionary of the Tamils|first=Vijaya |last=Ramaswamy |page=303 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |year=2007 |isbn=9780810864450 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H4q0DHGMcjEC}}</ref>
The community plays a significant role in the political and economic life of the Kongu Nadu region.<ref>[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-05-21/chennai/28179309_1_poll-observers-assembly-polls-poll-eve Gounder consolidation could pose headache to major parties - Times Of India<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Rahul-keen-to-test-western-belt-/articleshow/7498031.cms?referral=PM | title=Rahul keen to test western belt | newspaper=The Times of India | first=Jaya | last=Menon | date=15 February 2011 | accessdate=22 May 2016 }}</ref> Among them are businessmen who figure among the global leaders in several industrial sectors.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Gounder-consolidation-could-pose-headache-to-major-parties/articleshow/4557663.cms Gounders consolidation could pose headache to major parties]</ref>
==Wedding== The community has its own style of marriage ceremony. The ceremony is led by person called an Arumbukarar or Arumaikkarar.<ref>{{cite book|title=Peasant Society of Konku: A Study of right and left subastes in South India | first = Brenda | last= Beck|publisher= University of British Columbia Press, Vancouver| year = 1972 |page=299|ISBN=0-7748-0014-3}}</ref> A long song composed by [[Kambar (poet)|Kambar]], called "Mangala valthu", is usually sung.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil_nadu/Kambar-Kongunadus-Friend-or-Foe/2015/09/20/article3037320.ece |title=Kambar, Kongunadu's Friend or Foe? |first=B. Meenakshi |last=Sundaram |work=New Indian Express |date=20 September 2015 |accessdate=2016-09-12}}</ref> In the wedding ceremony the brother of the bride and sister of the groom play significant roles.<ref>{{cite book|title=Peasant Society of Konku: A Study of right and left subastes in South India | first = Brenda | last= Beck|publisher= University of British Columbia Press, Vancouver| year = 1972 |page=240|ISBN=0-7748-0014-3}}</ref>
