The '''Wardey''' is an [[ethnic community]] found in Southern [[Somalia]] ([[Lower Juba|Lower Jubba]]) and Eastern [[Kenya]],<ref name="BennunAman1995">{{cite book|last1=Bennun|first1=Leon A. |last2=Aman|first2=Rashid A. |last3=Crafter|first3=S. A. |title=Conservation of biodiversity in Africa: local initiatives and institutional roles : proceedings of the conference held at the National Museums of Kenya, 30 August-3 September, 1992|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TgREAQAAIAAJ|year=1995|publisher=Centre for Biodiversity, National Museums of Kenya|page=306}}</ref> mostly along the [[Tana River (Kenya)|Tana River]].  The Wardey are [[Pastoralism|pastoralist]] community. They live in [[Tana River County]] alongside with the [[Pokomo people|Pokomo]], [[Orma people|Orma]], Wailwana and Watta communities.  The [[tribe]] has a population of about 146,000 people (2011). They speak the [[Somali language]] and majority practice [[Islam]]. The origins of Wardey are unknown but some surrounding tribes say that they were originally from the [[Orma people|Orma tribe]] and some sources state they are a mixture of both Orma and [[dIR (clan)|DIR tribes.]]

